Hello everyone! I recently had an issue of trying to build a WPILib project on a netbook. I decided to share my solution in case anyone needs it. To get around this issue, I cloned the repo on a Github Codespace (Sign in to GitHub Â· GitHub), and used the following method to use the 2023.3.1 WPILib on it. The following json file, titled devcontainer.json goes in the folder .devcontainer on the working directory (if you donâ€™t have it, create it!).

{
    "image": "mcr.microsoft.com/devcontainers/universal:2",
    "postCreateCommand": "cd /opt && wget 'https://github.com/wpilibsuite/vscode-wpilib/releases/download/v2024.3.1/vscode-wpilib-2024.3.1.vsix'",
    "features": {
    },
    "customizations": {
      "vscode": {
        "extensions": ["/opt/vscode-wpilib-2024.3.1.vsix","vscjava.vscode-java-pack","vscjava.vscode-gradle"]
      }
    }
  }

Afterwards, you should be able to build projects and get highlighting, LSP features, etc. Some features are a bit finicky. Enjoy!

i will add that it is also really simple to add a status check that ensures code will build before, for example, allowing push to master

<repo>/.github/workflows/gradle.yml

name: Gradle Build

on:
  push:
    branches: [ "**" ]

permissions:
  contents: read

jobs:
  build:

    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v3
      - name: Set up JDK 17
        uses: actions/setup-java@v3
        with:
          java-version: '17'
          distribution: 'temurin'
      - name: Build with Gradle
        uses: gradle/gradle-build-action@bd5760595778326ba7f1441bcf7e88b49de61a25 # v2.6.0
        with:
          arguments: build
